      await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 10));
      const lines = raw.split('\n').filter(line => line.trim());
      // ... map (may throw here, now after the delay)
      return records;
  }
  ```

- **`validateRecords` and `transformRecords` never actually rejected** in the original (their `try/catch` paths were effectively dead code for the given logic), so the `try/catch` around their calls is retained only to preserve the exact error-prefix behavior if those functions were ever changed to throw.

- **`validateRecords` returns an object** (`{ validRecords, invalidCount }`) since async functions resolve a single value — the original callback's two extra arguments are bundled and destructured at the call site.

The `path` import is unused (as in the original) — I left it in to avoid changing anything beyond control flow.

